'''Student Human Rights Ordinance''' ({{lang-ko|학생인권조례}}) is an [[local ordinance|ordinance]] in operation in some cities and provinces in [[South Korea]]. It first began in [[Gyeonggi Province|Gyeonggi]] (2010) and expanded to [[Gwangju]] (2011), [[Seoul]] (2012), and the [[North Jeolla Province|Jeollabuk-do Province]] (2013) (North Jeolla Province). The primary objective of this ordinance is to guarantee [[Student rights|human rights of student]] and [[Youth rights|youth]] in South Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.sen.go.kr/lims/front/law.html?pAct=view&pPromulgationNo=2854 |title=Seoul Student Human Rights Ordinance |last=Kim |first=Yeong-sam |date=January 26, 2012 |website=Legal Public Administration Service, Seoul Metropolitan Office of Education |accessdate=January 21, 2014}} </ref>

==Distinctions Between Ordinances==

The four ordinances are very similar, however some cities neglected certain rights and actions. The Gyeonggi-do Student Human Rights Ordinance and [[Seoul Ordinance of Student Rights]] are the only two to include the right to not be discriminated against due to pregnancy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/경기도학생인권조례/(04853,20150227)/제5조|title=Gyeonggi-do Student Human Rights Ordinance Chapter 2, Section 1, Article 5|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/서울특별시학생인권조례/(06793,20180104)/제5조|title=Seoul Ordinance of Student Rights Chapter 2, Section 1, Article 5|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Rights surrounding gender and sexuality differs in each location. The Seoul ordinance as well as Gyeonggi-do ordinance include sexual orientation and gender identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/서울특별시학생인권조례/(06793,20180104)/제28조|title=Seoul Ordinance of Student Rights, Chapter 2, Section 10, Article 28|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/경기도학생인권조례/(04853,20150227)/제27조|title=Gyeonggi-do Ordinance of Student Human Rights, Chapter 2, Section 10, Article 27|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Gwangju ordinance only includes sexual orientation and Jeollabuk-do only includes gender equality. Seoul, Jeollabuk-do and Gyeonggi-do each dedicate a day to celebrate Student Human Rights Day in efforts to expand interest and participation in the human rights of the student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/서울특별시학생인권조례/(06793,20180104)/제37조|title=Seoul Ordinance of Student Rights, Chapter 3, Section 2, Article 37|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/전라북도학생인권조례/(03883,20140808)/제28조|title=Jeollabuk-do Ordinance of Student Right, Chapter 3, Section 1, Article 28|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/경기도학생인권조례/(04853,20150227)/제28조|title=Gyeonggi-do Ordinance of Student Human Rights, Chapter 3, Section 1, Article 28|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Gwangju has not created a day devoted to student human rights. Seoul’s ordinance mandates that basic human rights must always be upheld even if they are not listed in the ordinance.

The ordinances state that each city and province has to stay updated on a plan to ensure human rights. In Gwangju there is a survey conducted every two years to keep the human rights plan up to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/광주광역시학생인권보장및증진에관한조례/(04017,20111028)/제5조|title=Gwangju Ordinance of Student Rights, Chapter 2, Article 5|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> In Gyeonggi-do, the Superintendent of Public Instruction conducts an annual survey on student human rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/경기도학생인권조례/(04853,20150227)/제33조|title=Gyeoggi-do Ordinance of Student Human Rights, Chapter 3, Section 2, Article 33|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> In Seoul, the Superintendent conducts an annual survey on the actual conditions of student human rights and reflect the results in the drafting of the comprehensive human rights plan for students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/서울특별시학생인권조례/(06793,20180104)/제45조|title=Seoul Ordinance of Student Rights, Chapter 3, Section 5, Article 45|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> In Jeollabuk-do, the Chancellor conducts a survey on the condition of student human rights every year to reflect them in the education of human rights of students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.go.kr/자치법규/전라북도학생인권조례/(03883,20140808)/제33조|title=Jeollabuk-do Ordinance of Student Rights, Chapter 3, Section 2, Article 33|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

